'''Evgenia Vasilievna Shishkova''' ({{langx|ru|Евгения Васильевна Шишкова}}; 18 December 1972 – 29 January 2025) was a Russian [[figure skating]] coach and competitor. With her husband [[Vadim Naumov]], she was the [[1994 World Figure Skating Championships|1994 world champion]] and the [[1995–96 Champions Series Final]] champion.

== Career ==
Shishkova and Naumov were introduced in 1985 by Naumov's coach who wanted them to skate together.<ref name=HC980706/> Naumov initially rebuffed the idea because he did not wish to change partners; however after several tryouts, he and Shishkova agreed to be a team.<ref name=HC980706/> They began competing together in 1987.<ref name=poibio/>

In 1991, Shishkova/Naumov won bronze at their first [[1991 European Figure Skating Championships|European Championships]] in [[Sofia|Sofia, Bulgaria]] and placed 5th at the [[1991 World Figure Skating Championships|World Championships]] in [[Munich|Munich, Germany]]. During the next season, they competed at their first Olympics, the [[1992 Winter Olympics|1992 Olympics in Albertville, France]], placing fifth. Shishkova/Naumov won their first World Championships' medal–bronze–at the [[1993 World Figure Skating Championships|1993 World Championships]]. The pair placed 4th at the [[1994 Winter Olympics]] in [[Lillehammer|Lillehammer, Norway]]. They ended the season by becoming [[1994 World Figure Skating Championships|world champions]] in [[Chiba (city)|Chiba, Japan]] east of [[Tokyo]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zakurdaeva |first1=Irena |last2=Smirnova |first2=Lena |title=World figure skating champions and coaching pair Evgenia Shishkova and Vadim Naumov killed in plane crash |url=https://www.olympics.com/en/news/evgenia-shishkova-vadim-naumov-killed-plane-crash-figure-skating |publisher=International Olympic Committee |access-date=31 January 2025 |date=30 January 2025}}</ref>

