'''Vadim Vladimirovich Naumov''' ({{langx|ru|Вадим Владимирович Наумов}}; 7 April 1969 – 29 January 2025) was a Russian [[Pair skating|pair skater]]. With his wife [[Evgenia Shishkova]], he was the [[1994 World Figure Skating Championships|1994 world champion]] and the [[1995–96 Champions Series Final]] champion.

== Career ==
Shishkova and Naumov were introduced in 1985 by Naumov's coach who wanted them to skate together.<ref name=HC980706/> Naumov initially rebuffed the idea because he did not wish to change partners, however after a number of tryouts, he and Shishkova agreed to be a team .<ref name=HC980706/> They began competing together in 1987.<ref name=poibio/>

In 1991, Shishkova/Naumov won bronze at their first [[1991 European Figure Skating Championships|European Championships]] in [[Sofia|Sofia, Bulgaria]] and placed 5th at the [[1991 World Figure Skating Championships|World Championships]] in [[Munich|Munich, Germany]]. During the next season they competed at their first Olympics, the [[1992 Winter Olympics|1992 Olympics]] in [[Albertville|Albertville, France]] placing fifth. The pair won their first world medal–bronze–at the [[1993 World Figure Skating Championships|1993 World Championships]] in [[Prague]]. In 1993, the pair finished in 4th place at the [[1994 Winter Olympics]] in [[Lillehammer]], [[Norway]] and they ended the season by becoming [[1994 World Figure Skating Championships|world champions]] in [[Chiba (city)|Chiba, Japan]] east of [[Tokyo]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zakurdaeva |first1=Irena |last2=Smirnova |first2=Lena |title=World figure skating champions and coaching pair Evgenia Shishkova and Vadim Naumov killed in plane crash |url=https://www.olympics.com/en/news/evgenia-shishkova-vadim-naumov-killed-plane-crash-figure-skating |publisher=International Olympic Committee |access-date=31 January 2025 |date=30 January 2025}}</ref>

Shishkova/Naumov picked up their third world medal, a silver medal, in [[1995 World Figure Skating Championships|1995]]. From 1991–1995, they also won five [[European Figure Skating Championships|European Championships' figure skating]] medals. In February 1996, they won gold at the [[1995–96 Champions Series Final]] (later renamed the Grand Prix Final) in [[Paris]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Berlot |first1=Jean-Christophe |title=Champions Series Final earns high marks |url=https://skatingmagazine.azurewebsites.net/article/Skating_199604_02 |access-date=31 January 2025 |work=Skating Magazine |date=2 April 1996}}</ref>

